{"name": "fancy-einsum", "metadata": {"name": "fancy-einsum", "version": "0.0.3", "classifiers": ["License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Operating System :: OS Independent", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3"], "home_page": "https://github.com/Kiv/fancy_einsum", "license": "MIT", "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": [], "summary": "Drop-in replacement for torch/numpy einsum, with descriptive variable names in equations", "upload_time": 1643939624}, "documentation": ["# Fancy Einsum\n\nThis is a simple wrapper around `np.einsum` and `torch.einsum` that allows the use of self-documenting variable names instead of just single letters in the equations. Inspired by the syntax in [einops](https://github.com/arogozhnikov/einops).\n\nFor example, instead of writing:\n\n```python\nimport torch\ntorch.einsum('bct,bcs->bcts', a, b)\n```\n\nor \n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nnp.einsum('bct,bcs->bcts', a, b)\n```\n\nWith this library you can write:\n\n```python\nfrom fancy_einsum import einsum\neinsum('batch channels time1, batch channels time2 -> batch channels time1 time2', a, b)\n```\n\n"], "modules": [{"name": "fancy_einsum.test_torch", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "fancy_einsum.test_torch.tensor", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "draw", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "shape", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "fancy_einsum.test_torch.square_matrix", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "draw", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "fancy_einsum.test_torch.test_simple_matmul", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "mat", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "fancy_einsum.test_torch.matmul_compatible", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "draw", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "fancy_einsum.test_torch.test_ellipse_matmul", "asy